instruction:
A `struct` groups related data:

```cpp
struct Point {
    double x;
    double y;
};

Point p = {1.0, 2.0};  // initialise
p.x;   // access member
```

Run this.

starter:
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

struct Person {
    string name;
    int age;
    double height;
};

int main() {
    Person alice = {"Alice", 30, 1.68};
    Person bob   = {"Bob",   25, 1.80};

    cout << alice.name << " is " << alice.age << " years old." << endl;
    cout << bob.name   << " is " << bob.height << "m tall."    << endl;

    // Modify a field:
    alice.age++;
    cout << alice.name << " is now " << alice.age << "!" << endl;

    return 0;
}

instruction:
Structs can have methods — making them nearly identical to classes:

```cpp
struct Rectangle {
    double width, height;
    double area()     { return width * height; }
    double perimeter(){ return 2 * (width + height); }
};
```

